### Best Model Fit: Quasi-Poisson, GLMM

Now we are using the Performance package to obtain the Estimates and Contrast.Estimated marginal means indicated that predicted Aedes aegypti adult abundance varied across seasons, years, and communities. Across all seasonal and yearly combinations, rural households consistently exhibited higher predicted mosquito abundance than urban households after adjusting for repellent use, bed net use, water supply reliability, and waste disposal practices.

During the dry season of 2022, the predicted adult abundance was 0.12 mosquitoes per household in rural areas (95% CI: 0.08–0.18) compared with 0.08 in urban areas (95% CI: 0.05–0.13). In the rainy season of the same year, predicted abundance increased to 0.33 (95% CI: 0.22–0.50) in rural households and 0.24 (95% CI: 0.15–0.37) in urban households.

A similar pattern was observed in 2023. During the dry season, predicted adult abundance was 0.24 (95% CI: 0.17–0.35) in rural communities and 0.17 (95% CI: 0.11–0.26) in urban communities. The highest predicted mosquito abundance occurred during the rainy season of 2023, with rural households showing an expected abundance of 0.68 (95% CI: 0.46–1.01) compared with 0.48 (95% CI: 0.31–0.74) in urban households.

Overall, these results indicate that mosquito abundance increased during the rainy season and in the second year of surveillance, with rural communities consistently showing higher predicted adult Ae. aegypti abundance than urban communities.

